<HEAD>THE SCHOOL FOR ARROGANCE: A COMEDY.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE I. [The Hou&s;e of Sir <HI>PAUL PECKHAM.]</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LYDIA <HI>followed by</HI> MAC DERMOT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LYDIA.</SPEAKER>
<P>ONCE again, Mr. Mac Dermot, have done with this non&s;en&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Arrah, and why &s;o &s;coffi&s;h? Sure now a little bit of making love&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! Do me the favour to an&s;wer my que&s;tions. The Count, your ma&s;ter, is in love with Mi&s;s Lucy Peckham?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, and you may &s;ay that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is he really well born?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="2" REF="12">
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! As for that, honey, let him alone. The noble&s;t blood of France, aye, and what is better, of Ireland too, trickles to his finger's ends. The Villars and the O'Connol|lies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>And he wi&s;hes to marry into the family of the Peckhams?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>The divle a bit, my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is viry willing to marry the young Lady, but not her family. His pride and his pa&s;&s;ion have had many a tough battle about that, d'ye &s;ee. Only think! A direct de&s;cindant of the former kings of Ireland, and collateral cou&s;in to a pri&s;ent peer of France, to be&s;mear and be&s;moulder his dignity by rubbing it again&s;t porter butts, vinegar ca&s;ks, and beer barrels.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Lucy is indeed a lovely girl, animated to exce&s;s, and &s;ometimes apparently giddy and flighty: but &s;he has an excellent under&s;tanding, and a noble heart; and the&s;e are &s;uperior to birth, which is indeed a thing of mere accident.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, and that it is&mdash;I, a &s;imple Iri&s;hman, as I am&mdash;why now, I would have been born a duke, had they been civil enough to have a&s;ked my con&s;int.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Count fell in love with her at the convent, to which &s;he was &s;ent to improve her French.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And where I think you fir&s;t met with her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;&s;he &s;aw me friendle&s;s, and conceived a generous and di&s;intere&s;ted affection
<PB N="3" REF="13">
for me.&mdash;He has followed her to England; has taken apartments in our neighbourhood, and lives in &s;plendour&mdash;yet is not rich.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Um, um.&mdash;No&mdash;But then he is a Colonel in the Iri&s;h brigade; and, be&s;ide his pay, has &s;acrit &s;upplies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>From whom?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, and I don't believe he knows that him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's &s;trange!&mdash;His pride is ex|ce&s;&s;ive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;pake the truth, that now is his failing.&mdash;An if it was not for that, oh! he would be the jewel of a ma&s;ter!&mdash;He trates his infariors with contimpt, keeps his di&s;tance with his aquals, and values the rubbi&s;hing du&s;t of his great grandfathers above diamonds!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>His character is in perfect contra&s;t to that of his humble rival, Sir Samuel Sheepy; who, even when he addre&s;&s;es a footman, is all bows and affability; who&s;e chief di&s;cour&s;e is, Yes, if you plea&s;e, and, No, thank you; and who, in the company of his mi&s;tre&s;s, &s;tammers, blun|ders, and blu&s;hes, like a great boy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is it you till me? He the ri|val of the Count my ma&s;ter! That old&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>A bachelor, and only fifty; rich, of a good family, and a great favourite with Lady Peckham, by never having the courage to contradict her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, there now! You talk of the Count's pride! Here is this city lady as proud as ten counts! Her own coach hor&s;es, ready harne&s;&s;ed, don't carry their heads higher! And then &s;he is as in&s;olent, and as vulgar, and&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="4" REF="14">
Enter Lady <HI>PECKHAM</HI> and Sir <HI>SAMUEL SHEEPY,</HI> followed by two Footmen, in very &s;mart morn|ing jackets.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Here, fellers&mdash;go with the&s;e here cards <STAGE>[Footmen receive each a parcel of large cards, and are going]</STAGE> <Q>Oh! Tell that there butler to come to me&mdash;in&s;tantly.</Q>&mdash;And&mdash;Do you hear?&mdash;Vhen you comes back, get tho&s;e di&s;mal heads of yourn better powder'd; put on your noo liveries, and make your&s;elves a little like chri&s;tians.&mdash;The&s;e creeters are no better nur brootes, Sir Samooel! They are all &s;o mon&s;trous low, and wulgar!&mdash;I have a party to-night; I hopes you vill make von?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly, my Lady.</P>
</SP>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Vhy, vhere is this butler?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> BUTLER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am here, my Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is all the furniter rubb'd?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>All, my Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The m'ogany bright?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>As bees-wax can make it, my Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Bow pots in the china jars?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The picters on the hall &s;tair-ca&s;e &s;coured?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Clean, my Lady!&mdash;But, I&mdash; <STAGE>(he&s;i|tating)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You! You vhat?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am afraid their eyes and no&s;es will &s;oon di&s;appear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha!&mdash;Feller!&mdash;Are the noo prints come home?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="15">
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And the karakatoors hung up in the drawing room?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>All, my Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall come and &s;ee 'em, Sir Samooel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lady&s;hip has exqui&s;ite ta&s;te.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Sir Samooel!&mdash;Vell, feller?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Vhat do you &s;tand gaping at?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>"Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Vill you begone, feller?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Butler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh!&mdash;Yes, my Lady; <STAGE>(A&s;ide)</STAGE> and thank you too! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So, Mi&s;s! is Sir Paul come to town?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have not &s;een him, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Paul generally &s;leeps at our country &s;eat, at Hackney.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A plea&s;ant retreat, my Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Wa&s;tly! A wery paradi&s;e!&mdash;Vhere is my daughter, Mi&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And vhy don't you know? Plea&s;e to go and tell her Sir Samooel is here. <STAGE>[Exit Lydia.]</STAGE>&mdash;A young pur&s;on that my daughter has taken under her purtection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Seems mild and mode&s;t, my Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not too much of that, Sir Samooel.&mdash;Who <STAGE>(Surveying Mac Dermot)</STAGE>&mdash;pray, who are you, young man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I!&mdash;Faith, my Lady, I&mdash;I am&mdash;my|&s;ilf: Mac Dermot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Count's gintleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Gentleman!&mdash;Gentleman, indeed!&mdash;Count's gentleman!&mdash;Ha!&mdash;A kind of mungrel Count, Sir Samooel; half French,
<PB N="6" REF="16">
half Iri&s;h! As good a gentleman, I &s;uppo&s;e, as his footman here! I believes you have &s;een him though?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I think I once had the honor to meet him here, my Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>An honor, Sir Samooel, not of my &s;eeking, I a&s;&s;ure you! A&s;pires to the hand of Mi&s;s Loocy Peckham!&mdash;He!&mdash;An outlandi&s;h French foriner!&mdash;I hates 'em all! I looks upon none on 'em as no better nur &s;avages! Vhat do they vant vith us? Vhy our money, to be &s;ure! A parcel of beggars!&mdash;I vi&s;hes I vus Queen of England for von day only! I vould u&s;her my orders to take and conquer 'em all, and tran&s;|port 'em to the plantations, in&s;tead of negurs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have heard, my Lady, that the Count was my rival.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He your rival, Sir Samooel! He! A half bred, higglety-pigglety, Iri&s;h, French fortin hunter rival you indeed!&mdash; <STAGE>[Enter Lydia.]</STAGE>&mdash;Vell, Mi&s;s! Vhere is my daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>In her own apartment, Madam, dre&s;&s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady <HI>P.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She'll be down pre&s;ently, Sir Sa|mooel&mdash;Gentleman indeed! The Count's Gen|tleman! Ha! Pride and Poverty!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt Lady Peckham and Sir Samuel Sheepy.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Highly affronted)</STAGE> Pride!&mdash;By the holy foot&s;tool, but your Lady&s;hip and Lucifer are a pair!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Knocking.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here comes Sir Paul.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I will be after going.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no; &s;tay where you are.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="7" REF="17">
<HI>Enter Sir</HI> PAUL PECKHAM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! My &s;weet dear Liddy! You are the angel I wi&s;hed fir&s;t to meet! Come to my&mdash; <STAGE>(Running up to her.)</STAGE>&mdash;Why how now, hu&s;|&s;ey? Why &s;o &s;hy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;erve your tran&s;ports, Sir, for Lady Peckham.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lady!&mdash;But who have we here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Mac Dermot, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I remember&mdash;&s;ervant to the Count, my intended &s;on-in-law.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>The viry &s;ame, Sir. <STAGE>[Bows.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I hear an excellent character of your ma&s;ter. They tell me he is a fine, hearty, dauntle&s;s, &s;waggering fellow! If &s;o, he is a man of family, and the very hu&s;band for my Lucy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, thin, and he is all that!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>As for this Sir Samuel Sheepy, he &s;hall decamp&mdash;A water drinker! A bowing, &s;craping, &s;impering, ceremonious Sir! Never contradicts any body!&mdash;Dammee! An old ba|chelor! And he! He have the impudence to make love to my fine, young, &s;pirited wench!&mdash;But he is my Lady's choice!&mdash;Is &s;he within?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e we &s;hall have a fine breeze on this &s;ubject! But, what! Am I not the monarch, the Grand Seignior of this hou&s;e? Am I not ab&s;olute? Shall I not di&s;po&s;e of my daughter as I plea&s;e? Do you hear, young man? Go, pre&s;ent my compliments to the Count, and tell him I mean to give him a call this morning.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Lydia makes &s;igns to Mac Dermot to &s;tay.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am waiting for him here, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Waiting for him here, Sir! No, Sir! You cannot wait for him here, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="18">
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And, Sir! Why don't you go?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Count bid me, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And I bid you, Sir&mdash;Pack! Be|gone! <STAGE>[Exit Mac Dermot.]</STAGE>&mdash;Now we're alone, my dear Lydia&mdash;Why, where are you going, hu&s;&s;ey?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't you hear my Lady call?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Call? No.&mdash;And if &s;he did, let her call.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely, Sir, you would not have me offend her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Offend! Let me &s;ee who dare be offended with you in this hou&s;e! It is my will that you &s;hould be the Sultana!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You, my Queen of Hearts! You! My hou&s;e, my wealth, my &s;ervants, my&s;elf, all are yours!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>You talk unintelligibly, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do I? Why then I'll &s;peak plainer.&mdash;I am in love with you! You are a delicious crea|ture, and I am determined to make your for|tune!&mdash;I'll take you a hou&s;e up in Mary-le|bone; a neat &s;nug box; hire you &s;ervants, keep you a carriage, buy you rings, clothes, and jewels, and come and &s;up with you every eve|ning!&mdash;Do you under&s;tand me now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perfectly, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, and&mdash;hay!&mdash;Does not the plan tickle your fancy? Do not your veins tin|gle, your heart beat, your&mdash;hay? What &s;ay you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I really, Sir, don't know what to &s;ay&mdash;except that I cannot comply, unle&s;s a
<PB N="9" REF="19">
Lady, whom I think it my duty to con&s;ult, &s;hould give her con&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What Lady? Who?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lady Peckham, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My wife!&mdash;Zounds! Are you mad? Tell my wife?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall further a&s;k the advice of your &s;on and daughter, who will wonder at your cha|rity, in taking a poor orphan like me under your protection; <Q>will be happy to &s;ee them|&s;elves ruined for my &s;ake, and will profit by the example of &s;o venerable a father.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Poh! Non&s;en&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>A little farther off, if you plea&s;e, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nearer! Angel! Nearer!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll rai&s;e the hou&s;e, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Help!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My handkerchief! You &s;weet&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> EDMUND.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lydia! Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How now, Sir!&mdash; <STAGE>[A&s;ide to Lydia.]</STAGE> Hem!&mdash;Say it was a mou&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is the matter, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What's that to you, Sir?&mdash;What do you want, Sir? Who &s;ent for you, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>I perceive you are not well, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>How were you taken?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Taken!&mdash; <STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> Young &s;coundrel!&mdash;Take your&s;elf away, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible, Sir! You tremble! Your looks are di&s;ordered! Your eyes wild!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> Here's a dog!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="20">
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;o obliging, Mi&s;s Lydia, as to run and inform Lady Peckham how ill my father is!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you imp! <STAGE>[Stopping Lydia]</STAGE> Lydia! Stay where you are&mdash;You audacious!&mdash;Will you begone?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I certainly will not, Sir, while I &s;ee you in &s;uch a way!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Way, Sir!&mdash;Very well, Sir!&mdash;Very well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll reach you a chair, Sir&mdash;Pray &s;it down&mdash;Pray cool your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, that I were cooling you in a hor&s;epond!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are growing old, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You lie, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hould be more careful of your|&s;elf&mdash;Shall I &s;end for a phy&s;ician?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> Dammee, but I'll phy&s;ic you! I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><STAGE>Enter a <HI>MAN-COOK.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cook.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;oup is ready, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cook.</SPEAKER>
<P>Knew your wor&s;hip's hour&mdash;Never made better in my life&mdash;Rich and high! Ju&s;t to your wor&s;hip's palate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, fellow, don't you &s;ee I'm very ill?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cook.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ill, Sir Paul!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That my eyes are wild, that I tremble, am old, and want a phy&s;ician?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cook.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord! Sir Paul! I have been your phy&s;ician for the&s;e fifteen years!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, I'm ill; and want cool|ing!
<PB N="11" REF="21">
A&s;k that &s;coundrel el&s;e&mdash;I'm dying! So &s;erve up your do&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cook.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha! Yes, your wor&s;hip. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Muttering as he goes off]</STAGE> A &s;ly, invi|dious&mdash;The demure dog has a mind to her him|&s;elf&mdash;Yes, yes!&mdash;Oh! Dammee, pitiful Peter, but I'll fit you! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;ee, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Shrugging]</STAGE> I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t leave this family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leave! Why, charming Lydia, will you afflict me thus? Have I not declared my purpo&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Which cannot be accompli&s;hed. You promi&s;e marriage, but your father will never con&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then we will marry without his con|&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no! Do not hope it! When I marry, it &s;hall be to render both my hu&s;band and my&s;elf re&s;pectable, and happy: not to em|bitter, not to di&s;honour both.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a <HI>FOOTMAN.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Foot.</SPEAKER>
<P>A per&s;on, who calls him&s;elf Mr. Do|rimont, enquires for you, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens! Can it be? Shew him up in&s;tantly. <STAGE>[Exit Footman.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;eem alarmed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no! Overjoyed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;carcely can tell you. A gentleman who u&s;ed to vi&s;it me in the convent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you been long acquainted?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="22">
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Little more than two years; during which he was my monitor, con&s;oler, and guide</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Seeing him before he enters]</STAGE> His ap|pearance&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is poor; but his heart is rich in bene|volence. Pray leave us. <STAGE>[Exit Edmund.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mr. DORIMONT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Running to meet him]</STAGE> Ah! Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am happy to have found you once again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Sir, has brought you to Eng|land?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Bu&s;ine&s;s; part of which was to &s;ee you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have been always generous and kind&mdash;Yet I am &s;orry you &s;hould &s;ee me thus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why? <STAGE>[Eagerly]</STAGE> What are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>An humble dependant&mdash;A lady's companion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! Why did you leave the convent without informing me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twas unexpected.&mdash;You had for|borne your vi&s;its; and I feared death, or &s;ome misfortune. At my mother's decea&s;e, the young lady with whom I live having an affection for me, and &s;eeing me de&s;erted, offered to take me with her to England, promi&s;ing I &s;hould rather be her friend than her companion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And has &s;he kept her word?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>On her part faithfully, tenderly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That is &s;ome con&s;olation!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>But&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>She has a mother, who does not fail to make in&s;eriority feelingly under&s;tand it&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="23">
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[With &s;ome emotion]</STAGE> Indeed!&mdash; <STAGE>[Col|lecting him&s;elf]</STAGE> But with whom were you in &s;uch earne&s;t conver&s;ation when I entered?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>The brother of my young lady: a gentleman worthy your e&s;teem.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And worthy yours?&mdash;You blu&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you blame me for being ju&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;He is rich, young, and hand|&s;ome.&mdash;Do you often meet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>We do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are lovely, inexperienced, and unprotected!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fear nothing&mdash;I &s;hall not ea&s;ily for|get my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Earne&s;tly]</STAGE> I hope not.&mdash;But what does he &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>That he loves me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is that all?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;He offers me &s;ecret marriage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Secret</HI> marriage!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee the danger, and wi&s;h to &s;hun it.&mdash;You may find me &s;ome place of refuge in France.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Can you &s;o ea&s;ily renounce all the flattering pro&s;pects love has rai&s;ed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and not only them, but love it&s;elf, when it is my duty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Noble-minded girl!&mdash;Remain where you are&mdash;Nay, indulge your hopes; for know, your lover will be honoured by your hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!&mdash;Honoured.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Honoured!&mdash;By birth you are greatly his &s;uperior.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can you be &s;erious?&mdash;Oh, trifle not
<PB N="14" REF="24">
with a too trembling heart!&mdash;Why did my mo|ther conceal this &s;ecret from me?&mdash;Or, if true, why die and leave it unrevealed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There were rea&s;ons&mdash;She was not your mother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not!&mdash;Oh, &s;ir! You have conjured up ten thou&s;and bu&s;y thoughts!&mdash;Is my mother living?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why has he &s;o long for&s;aken me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That mu&s;t be told hereafter. Be patient&mdash;wait the event.&mdash;You are acquainted, I think, with Count Conolly Villars?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>He vi&s;its here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have bu&s;ine&s;s with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Sir! I fear you will meet a cool reception! Your humble appearance and his pride will but ill agree.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fear not&mdash;My bu&s;ine&s;s is to lower his pride.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir! He may in&s;ult you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Humble though I my&s;elf am, I hope to teach him humility. To vi&s;it you, and to accompli&s;h this, was the purport of my jour|ney.&mdash;Adieu for the pre&s;ent&mdash;Think on what I have &s;aid; and, though by birth you are noble, remember, virtue alone is true nobility.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Lydia rings. Exit Mr. Dorimont, and enter Lucy: her dre&s;s more characteri&s;tic of the girl than of the woman; and her manner full of life, but tempered by the mo&s;t delicate &s;en&s;ibility.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Lydia! Any news for me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Mac Dermot has been here, with
<PB N="15" REF="25">
the Count's compliments; but in reality to &s;ee if Lady Peckham were at home. You know how much he wi&s;hes to avoid her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and I don't wonder at it.&mdash;She has ju&s;t been with me, u&s;hering her orders, as &s;he calls it.&mdash;"I de&s;ires, Mi&s;s, you vill receive Sir Samooel Sheepy as your intended &s;pou&s;e."&mdash;And &s;o &s;he has &s;ent me here to be courted; and the inamorato is coming, as &s;oon as he can take breath and courage!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why, my dear, do you indulge your&s;elf in mocking your mamma?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lydia, I mu&s;t either laugh or cry; and, though I laugh, I a&s;&s;ure you it is often with an aching heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear girl!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, however, you will own there is no great harm in laughing a little at this charm|ing Adonis, this whim&s;ical lover of mine!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can his rea&s;on be for making love to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's a que&s;tion! Pray, my dear, do you never look in your gla&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Um&mdash;yes&mdash;But does he never look in his gla&s;s too?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps his &s;ight begins to decay.&mdash;But are not you alarmed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not you love the Count?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Um&mdash;Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! And you know how violent and prejudiced Lady Peckham is!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perfectly! But I have Sir Paul on my &s;ide; and, as for Sir Samuel, he was dandled &s;o
<PB N="16" REF="26">
long in the nur&s;ery, and is &s;till &s;o much of the aukward, ba&s;hful boy, that he will never dare to put the que&s;tion directly to me; and I am de|termined never to under&s;tand him till he does.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here he comes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't leave me.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SIR SAMUEL SHEEPY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Bowing with trepidation]</STAGE> Madam&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Madam&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Curt&s;ying and mimicking]</STAGE> Sir&mdash;Hem! Sir&mdash; <STAGE>[A&s;ide to Lydia]</STAGE> Count his bows!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I am afraid&mdash;I am trouble&s;ome.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;Hem!&mdash;A gentleman of your merit&mdash;Hem!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Continues bowing through mo&s;t of the &s;cene]</STAGE> Oh, Madam!&mdash;I am afraid&mdash;Hem!&mdash;You are bu&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Curt&s;ying to all his bows]</STAGE> Sir&mdash;Hem!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do me the honour to bid me be|gone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely, Sir, you would not have me guilty of rudene&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> What a blunder!&mdash;Ma|dam&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I a&s;k ten thou&s;and pardons!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good manners require&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That I &s;hould begone without bidding. <STAGE>[Going]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> I &s;uppo&s;e I'm wrong again&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I didn't &s;ay &s;o, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Turning quick]</STAGE> Didn't you, Ma|dam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>A per&s;on of your politene&s;s, breed|ing, and accompli&s;hments&mdash;Hem!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="17" REF="27">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> She's laughing at me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ought to be treated with all reve|rence. <STAGE>[Curt&s;ying with ironic gravity.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> Yes! She's making a fool of me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!&mdash;Were you plea&s;ed to &s;peak, Sir?&mdash;Hem!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hem!&mdash;Not a word, Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>This will be a witty conver&s;ation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I pre&s;ume, Sir&mdash;Hem!&mdash;You have &s;omething to communicate.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Yes, Madam, I mean no, Madam&mdash;No&mdash;Nothing&mdash;Hem!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing, Sir Samuel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hem!&mdash;Nothing&mdash;Nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then may I take the liberty, Sir, to enquire&mdash;Hem!&mdash;What the purport of your vi&s;it is?&mdash;Hem!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The&mdash;the&mdash;the&mdash;Hem!&mdash;The&mdash;purport is&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I&mdash;I have really forgotten!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, pray, Sir, take time to recollect your&s;elf&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I am &s;ure, Sir Samuel&mdash;Hem!&mdash;You have &s;omething to &s;ay to me&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;No&mdash;no&mdash;nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fie! Sir Samuel! Nothing to &s;ay to a lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No!&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I never had any thing to &s;ay to ladies in my life! That is&mdash;Yes&mdash;Yes&mdash;I own&mdash;I have &s;omething of the&mdash;the utmo&s;t&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A thing which&mdash;lies at my heart!&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy!&mdash;Sir Samuel!&mdash;Hem!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="28">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Which I&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Have long&mdash;But I will take &s;ome other opportunity. <STAGE>[Offering to go.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no means, Sir Samuel! You have quite alarmed me! I am impatient to hear! I am afraid you are troubled in mind&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Yes, Madam&mdash;Rather&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I declare, I thought &s;o! I am very &s;orry! Perhaps you are afraid of death?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet you are not &s;o very old!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I would not have you terrify your&s;elf too much&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I perceive I have gue&s;&s;ed it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam! Hem! No, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>No!&mdash;What then is this important &s;ecret?&mdash;Nay, pray tell me&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hem! N&mdash;n&mdash;n&mdash;n not at pre&s;ent, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Sir Samuel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Some other time, Madam&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>And can you be &s;o cruel to me? Can you? I declare, I &s;hall dream about you! Shall think I &s;ee you in your winding-&s;heet! Or &s;ome &s;uch frightful figure! And &s;hall wake all in a tremble&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A tremble indeed, Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>And won't you tell me, Sir Samuel? Won't you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>N&mdash;n&mdash;n&mdash;n not at pre&s;ent, Ma|dam&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="19" REF="29">
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, if you won't, Sir Samuel, I mu&s;t leave you; for what you have &s;aid has ab|&s;olutely given me the vapours!&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I, Madam!&mdash;Have I given you the vapours?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, you have, Sir Samuel; and &s;hockingly too! You have put &s;uch gloomy ideas into my mind!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me, Madam&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;alts, Lydia!&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, Madam, you&mdash;you are not <HI>very</HI> ill!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I &s;hall be better in another room&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> Yes, yes; 'tis my company that has given her the vapours. <STAGE>[Aloud]</STAGE> Shall I&mdash; <STAGE>[Confu&s;edly offering his arm.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no&mdash;Stay where you are, Sir Samuel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> She wants to be rid of me!&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lucy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only, remember, you are under a promi&s;e to tell me your &s;ecret&mdash;Hem!&mdash;If you don't, I &s;hall certainly &s;ee your gho&s;t! Remem|ber&mdash;Hem! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam&mdash;I&mdash; <STAGE>[Not knowing whether to go or &s;tay]</STAGE>&mdash; <STAGE>[To Lydia]</STAGE> Mi&s;s Lydia&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you would&mdash;hem! be &s;o civil, I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir! I have the vapours as bad as Mi&s;s Lucy! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sam.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have you?&mdash;Hem! Ble&s;s me! <Q>Death! Winding-&s;heets! Gho&s;ts!&mdash;Gloomy ideas indeed&mdash;Hem!&mdash;She was laughing at
<PB N="20" REF="30">
me! I am &s;ure &s;he was! Hem! All my life long have I been laughed at by young co|quetti&s;h girls! Yet I can't for&s;ake 'em! Then</Q> the vapours! My old trick! I always give young ladies the vapours! I make 'em ill! They are always &s;ick of me! Hem!&mdash;'Tis very &s;trange that I can't learn to talk without having a word to &s;ay! A thing &s;o common too! Why can't I give my&s;elf monkey airs, &s;kip here and there, be &s;elf-&s;ufficient, impertinent, and be|have like a puppy, purpo&s;ely to plea&s;e the la|dies? What! Is there no &s;uch thing to be found as a woman who can love a man for his mo|de&s;ty? This foreign count, now, my rival, is quite a different thing! He <STAGE>[Mimicking]</STAGE>&mdash;He walks with a &s;traight back, and a cocked-up chin, and a &s;trut, and a &s;tride, and &s;tares, and takes &s;nuff, and&mdash;! Yes, yes! He's the man for the ladies! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="21" REF="31">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>SCENE,</HI> an Apartment in the Hou&s;e of Sir <HI>PAUL PECKHAM.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LYDIA.</SPEAKER>
<P>I CANNOT forget it&mdash;My father alive! And I of noble de&s;cent!&mdash;'Tis very &s;trange!&mdash;Hope, doubt, and apprehen&s;ion are all in arms! Imagination hurries me beyond all li|mits of probability!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> EDMUND.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why do you thus &s;eek &s;olitude?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>To indulge thought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has your friend brought you bad news?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>What has he &s;aid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Strange things!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens!&mdash;What?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>You would think me a lunatic, were I to repeat them.</P>
</SP>
<Q REND="margQuotes"><SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lydia! I conjure you not to keep me on the rack!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was enjoined &s;ilence, but I feel my heart has no &s;ecrets for you&mdash;Yet, you will laugh.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ungenerous Lydia!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; you will think me mad.</P>
</SP></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lydia, you are unju&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I?&mdash;Well then, I am told&mdash;Would you believe it?&mdash;I am told that my family is illu&s;trious!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good heavens!&mdash;'Tis true! I feel it is true! Charming Lydia, <STAGE>[Kneeling]</STAGE> thus let love pay you that homage which the world, blind and malignant, denies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e, Edmund. Birth can at be&s;t but confer imaginary dignity; there is no true gran|deur but of mind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some one is coming!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, aye! Get you gone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am all tran&s;port!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! Away!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Edm.</SPEAKER>
<P>My angel! <STAGE>[Ki&s;&s;es her hand.]</STAGE></P>
<STAGE>[Exit ha&s;tily.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FOOTMAN, <HI>introducing</HI> Mr. DORIMONT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Foot.</SPEAKER>
<P>A gentleman to you, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;udden return, Sir, is kind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have bethought me. The mo|ment is critical, and what I have to communi|cate of importance. Are we &s;ecure?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>We are. This is my apartment. <STAGE>[Lydia goes and bolts the door.]</STAGE> Have you &s;een the Count, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No. But I have written to him anonymou&s;ly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>And why anonymou&s;ly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To rou&s;e his feelings, wound his vanity, and excite his anger. His &s;lumbering faculties mu&s;t be awakened.&mdash;Is he kind to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="23" REF="33">
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>No. Yet I believe him to be gene|rous, benevolent, and noble of heart; though his habitual haughtine&s;s gives him the appear|ance of qualities the very rever&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Worthy, kind girl!&mdash;You were born for the con&s;olation of a too unfortunate father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Again you remind me that I have a father. Why am I not allowed to &s;ee him? Why am I not &s;uffered to fly into his arms?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He dreads le&s;t his wretched and pitiable condition &s;hould make you meet him with coldne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! How little does he know my heart! Yet &s;peak; tell me, what mon&s;ter was the cau&s;e of his mi&s;ery?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The mon&s;ter Pride.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pride!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your mother's pride, which fir&s;t &s;quandered his wealth, and next endangered his life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>How you alarm me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A de&s;picable di&s;pute for preceden|cy was the occa&s;ion of a duel, in which your father killed his antagoni&s;t, who&s;e enraged fa|mily, by &s;uborning witne&s;&s;es, cau&s;ed him to be convicted of murder, obliged him to fly the kingdom, and with your mother wander under a borrowed name, a fugitive in di&s;tant coun|tries.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens!&mdash;But why leave me ig|norant of my birth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That, being unfortunate, you might be humble: that you might not grieve after happine&s;s which you &s;eemed de&s;tined
<PB N="24" REF="34">
not to enjoy. 'Twas the precaution of a fond father, de&s;irous to alleviate, if not &s;uccour your di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! How I burn to &s;ee him!&mdash;Is he not in danger? Is his life &s;ecure?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He him&s;elf can &s;carcely &s;ay. His enemies have di&s;covered him, are hot in pur&s;uit, and fertile in &s;tratagems and &s;nares. They know that ju&s;tice is now bu&s;ied in his behalf; but ju&s;tice is &s;low, and revenge is re&s;tle&s;s.&mdash;Their activity, I hear, is redoubled.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Guard, I conjure you, guard my fa|ther's &s;afety! Let me fly to &s;eek him! Conduct me to his feet!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He wi&s;hed you fir&s;t to be informed of his true &s;ituation; le&s;t, knowing him to be noble, you &s;hould expect to &s;ee him in all the pomp of affluence, in&s;tead of meeting a poor, dejected, forlorn old man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>His fears are unju&s;t; injurious to every feeling of filial affection and duty! The little I have I will freely partake with him. My clothes, the diamond which my &s;uppo&s;ed mother left me, whatever I po&s;&s;e&s;s &s;hall in&s;tantly be &s;old for his relief: my life &s;hall be devoted to &s;often his &s;orrows. Oh that I could prove my&s;elf wor|thy to be his daughter! Oh that I could pour out my &s;oul to &s;ecure his felicity!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Forbear!&mdash;Let me breathe!&mdash;Affection cannot find utterance!&mdash;Oh! this melting heart!&mdash;My child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My Lydia!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My child!&mdash;My daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="35">
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Falling at his feet]</STAGE> Can it be?&mdash;My father!&mdash;Oh ec&s;ta&s;y!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e, my child!&mdash;Suffer me to appea&s;e my melting heart!&mdash;Oh, delight of my eyes!&mdash;Why is not your brother like you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>My brother! Who? Have I a bro|ther?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Count is your brother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis too much!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He is not worthy &s;uch a &s;i&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;i&s;ter of the Count! I!&mdash;Ah! Nature, thy in&s;tincts are fabulous: for, were they not, his heart would have beaten as warmly toward me, as mine has done for him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will make him blu&s;h at his ar|rogance. You &s;hall witne&s;s his confu&s;ion; which &s;hall be public, that it may be effectual.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would you have me avoid explana|tion with him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, for the pre&s;ent.&mdash;I mean to &s;ee him. Our meeting will be warm; but he &s;hall feel the authority of a father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you are a &s;tranger to him, I fear le&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, no. He knows me, but knows not all his obligations to me.&mdash;I have &s;ecretly &s;upplied him with money, and gained him pro|motion; which he has vainly attributed to his per&s;onal merits. But I mu&s;t be gone. My bur|thened heart is ea&s;ed! Once more, dear child of my affections, be prudent. I have much to ap|prehend; but, &s;hould the pre&s;ent moment prove benign, my future days will all be peace!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Knocking heard at the chamber door.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="36">
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Alarmed]</STAGE> Who's there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Without]</STAGE> 'Tis I!&mdash;Open the door!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am bu&s;y, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! Open the door, Itell you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Paul.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And does he take the liberty to come into your apartment?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir, he will take any liberty he can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't you open the door?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are &s;urrounded by danger and temptation!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have no fears for me, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will you open the door, I &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Let him come in. <STAGE>[Lydia unbolts the door.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SIR PAUL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What is the rea&s;on, you dear little baggage, that you always &s;hut your&s;elf up &s;o carefully?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are one of the rea&s;ons, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! You need not be afraid of me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm <HI>not</HI> afraid of you, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why that's right. I'm come to talk matters over with you. My Lady's out&mdash;a wi&s;iting. <STAGE>[Mimicking]</STAGE>&mdash;The coa&s;t is clear. I have &s;ecured my gracele&s;s dog of a &s;on&mdash;I &s;u&s;pect&mdash;!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But it won't do! Mind! Take the hint!&mdash;I've heard of an excellent hou&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are running on as u&s;ual, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>With a convenient back door!&mdash;I'll be&s;peak you a carriage! Choo&s;e your own liveries! Keep as many footmen as you plea&s;e! Indulge in every thing your heart can wi&s;h! Operas, balls, routs, ma&s;querades! Rotten Row of a Sunday! Town hou&s;e and country hou&s;e! Bath, Bri&s;tol, or Buxton! Hot wells, or cold wells! Only&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Hay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I mu&s;t not hear &s;uch ribaldry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed but you mu&s;t, my dear&mdash;How will you help it? You can't e&s;cape me now! I have you fa&s;t! No &s;capegrace &s;coundrel of a&mdash;! <STAGE>[Mr. Dorimont comes forward]</STAGE> And &s;o&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Sternly]</STAGE> And &s;o, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! <STAGE>[Pau&s;e]</STAGE> And &s;o! <STAGE>[Look|ing round]</STAGE> Locked up together! You were bu&s;y!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, very, Sir! Perhaps you have a hou&s;e your&s;elf, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>With a convenient back door?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So far from offering the lady &s;uch an in&s;ult, Sir, I am almo&s;t tempted to cha&s;ti&s;e that impotent effrontery which has been &s;o dar|ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hem!&mdash;You are very civil, Sir! And, as a return for your compliment, I am ready to do my&s;elf the plea&s;ure, Sir, to wait on you down &s;tairs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lydia.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;pare you the trouble, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Though this Lady's re&s;idence here will be but &s;hort, I would have you beware, Sir, how you &s;hock her ears again, with a propo&s;al &s;o vile!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="26" REF="38">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="27" REF="39">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="40">
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Paul.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your caution is kind, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. <HI>Dor.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry it is nece&s;&s;ary, Sir! What! The head of a hou&s;e! The father of a family! Oh! Shame! He who, tottering on the brink of the grave, would gratify appetites which he no longer knows, by reducing the happy to mi&s;ery and the innocent to guilt, de|&s;erves to &s;ink into that contempt and infamy into which he would plunge unwary &s;implicity.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>SCENE,</HI> the apartment of the Count, an elegant room, with chairs, &s;opha, gla&s;&s;es, pic|tures, &amp;c.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>MAC DERMOT</HI> and <HI>PICARD,</HI> with a letter in his hand, meeting.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, Mr. Picard; what have you got there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Von lettre for Mon&s;ieur le Comte.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, give it me, and go about your bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P>No! I not go about my bi&s;ane&s;s! My bi&s;ane&s;s is to &s;peaka to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>To me!&mdash;And what is it you want?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Mon argent!</HI> My vage an my <HI>cong&eacute;!</HI> My di&s;mi&s;s!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, man alive!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are dee&mdash;dee factotum to dee Count. He &s;uffare no &s;omebody to &s;peaka to him; &s;o I am come &s;peaka to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Arrah now, and are you crazy? Quit the &s;arvice of a Count! Your rea&s;on, man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P>My <HI>rai&s;on</HI> is you talka too mo&s;h enough; he no talk at all! I follow him from France;
<PB N="29" REF="41">
I yet live vid him by and by four month, he no &s;peaka to me four vord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>What then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vat den!&mdash;<HI>Je &s;uis Fran&ccedil;ois, moi!</HI> I ave dee tongue for a dee &s;peaka; I mus &s;peaka; I vila &s;peaka! He not &s;o mo&s;h do me dee <HI>faveur</HI> to &s;cold a me! I ave leave dee be&s;t Madame in Paris for <HI>Mon&s;ieur le Comte&mdash;Quelle Femme!</HI> Her tongue vas nevare &s;till! Nevare! She &s;cold and &s;he clack, clack, clack, clack, clack, from all day an all night! Oh! It vas delight to hear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o you want to be &s;colded?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Oui</HI>&mdash;I love to be &s;cold, I love to &s;cold; to be fall out an to be fall in&mdash;<HI>C'e&s;t mon gout</HI>&mdash;Dee plai&s;ir of my life! <HI>J'irai crever!</HI> If I no &s;peak I bur&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And is it you now, &s;palpeen, that would chatter in the pri&s;ence of the Count?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shatter! Shatter! Ha! Vat you mean &s;hatter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have not you roa&s;t beef and plum pudding?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vat is roas beef, vat is plom boodin, gotam! if I no &s;peaka? I ave a dee Ma&s;ter in France dat &s;tarva me, dat pay me no <HI>gage,</HI> dat leave a me <HI>tout en guenilles;</HI> all rag an tattare; yet I love him better as mo&s;h! <HI>Pourquoi?</HI> <STAGE>[Af|fectionately]</STAGE> <HI>Helas! J'&eacute;tois &s;on cher ami!</HI> His dear fren! He talka to me, I talka to him! I laugh at his joke, he laugh <HI>au&s;&s;i,</HI> an I am both togeder &s;o happy as dee prince! But dee Count&punc; Oh! He as proud!&mdash;Ha!&mdash;<HI>Comme &ccedil;a.</HI> <STAGE>[Mimick|ing.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="42">
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poh! Now&mdash;My good fillow, have patience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Pic.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Patience! Moi!</HI>&mdash;I no <HI>patience</HI>&mdash;If I no &s;peak I am <HI>enrag&eacute;</HI>&mdash;I am French&mdash;I am Picard&mdash;Ven dee heart is full dee tongue mus run! I give you varn&mdash;Let my Ma&s;ta &s;peak, or I &s;hall di&s;mi&s;&s;a my Ma&s;ta!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here comes the Count! Stand back, man, and hould your tongue!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Enter the Count, followed by two Footmen, in hand|&s;ome liveries. Footmen place them&s;elves in the back ground. Mac Dermot comes a little for|ward.]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P>The more I reflect on my own infa|tuation, the more I am a&s;toni&s;hed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Traver&s;ing the &s;tage]</STAGE> A man of my birth! My rank! <Q>So to forget him&s;elf!&mdash;Still &s;he is an angel!&mdash;But the family of a cit!</Q>&mdash;A brewer's daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mac D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Count.</SPEAKER>
